# Visual Hierarchy Standards

## 1) Layout Structure
- Use a clear page hierarchy: header -> primary panel (guidance) -> main content -> secondary panel (details).
- Keep panel ownership strict: guidance for direction, main content for document context, details for decisions.

## 2) Block/Card Pattern
- Render each review unit as one block/card row.
- Use consistent spacing between rows and consistent internal padding.
- Show one block label per unit (`Block X`) and avoid duplicate headings inside pane content.

## 3) Highlight States
- `active`: blue emphasis (highest attention).
- `issue`: yellow emphasis (secondary attention).
- `default`: neutral surface and border.
- `completed`: muted treatment.
- Prefer row-level highlight over noisy inline emphasis unless required by interaction.

## 4) Button Hierarchy
- Exactly one primary CTA per screen/state.
- Secondary actions must be visually de-emphasized.
- Avoid duplicate actions that produce equivalent outcomes.

## 5) Pane System
- Use a consistent left/right pane layout where applicable.
- Keep subtle but clear pane differentiation (for example, neutral source vs tinted translated pane).
- Maintain vertical alignment between corresponding panes.

## 6) Typography Roles
- Section titles: clear and high-signal.
- Block labels: compact meta markers.
- Body text: readable content-first text.
- Meta text: subdued supporting information.

## 7) Clarity Rules
- Do not duplicate the same information across guidance, diff, and details panels.
- Use `Block` as canonical review terminology in user-facing review UI.
- Do not mix `content` or `segment` for the same review unit.
- Prioritize scanability and clarity over density.
